<br>
Turning his gaze to the unnaturally pale Stormygale, he asked Athene quietly &quot;Can you tell me what is happening?  I came as soon as I learned there was trouble.&quot;  He cast Quiescence  on Saphron as he listened, among the spells benefits was a temporary respite from acute pain.<br>
<br>
Kyusz <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#141419><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title><A HREF="http://www.ezboard.com/promotions/csc.html" TARGET="_blank" ><IMG SRC="http://www.ezboard.com/image/cscicon3.gif" WIDTH="20" HEIGHT="20" BORDER="0" align="absmiddle"></A> <A HREF=http://pub148.ezboard.com/bthewordsofnagafen.showUserPublicProfile?gid=athene>Athene</A>&nbsp; <IMG HEIGHT=10 WIDTH=10 SRC="http://home.mindspring.com/~abvogan/_uimages/ahstarsm.gif" BORDER=0></span><br> <span class=usertitle>CoN Member</span><br>  Posts: 118<br> <font color=#7A8798>(8/19/03 7:25 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub148.ezboard.com/fthewordsofnagafenmuirlansweeklypics.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=142.topic&index=106>Reply</a>    <br>ezSupporter<br> <BR><img src=http://home.mindspring.com/~abvogan/eye.JPG WIDTH=60 HEIGHT=60></td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title>   Re: The Fraud</span><hr size=1> Athene’s relief was immediate and unexpected.  The man—the iksar, rather—was professional.  He bore a gentle aura of quiet self-confidence and genuine concern.  It seemed unusual for an iksar, but then she had known few well.  <br>
<br>
“Please,&quot; she began, &quot;set down your bags and make yourself comfortable, Kyusz.”  She looked around the room for a suitable chair for one with a tail and was grateful to see Kalyndria pull forward a low stool, the one the wee people of the tree sometimes used for a table top.  It would do well.  <br>
<br>
When Kyusz was comfortably seated, Athene spoke quietly to him, trying to tell the story as quickly as she might.  She unsure how much time she might have before Stormygale roused up to spew who knew what these days—words, alcohol, venom ….  And for the moment, Saphron rested comfortable.<br>
<br>
“Stormygale has been sick for some time.  The illness is both physical and … mental, … and in the last few days, its nature has changed again.”<br>
<br>
Kyusz looked from Athene to Stormygale.  He hoped the druidess would be able to offer an explanation a bit better than this, but he waited, sitting patiently and listened.<br>
<br>
Athene's words flowed in a torrent of words.  “She’s been unhappy for a long time.  ... Actually, I’ve never known her <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><em>joyful</em><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--> for any <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><em>great</em><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--> stretch of time.  She had a lonely childhood, … raised in the Burning Woods alone, … hidden.  She didn’t actually come to the guild hall until she was already a young woman.  And she’s <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><em>always</em><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--> been high spirited, as we say.  Her father was—indeed, her father <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><em>is</em><!--EZCODE ITALIC END-->—Teir’dal.”  Athene paused for a moment noticing Kyusz’s puzzled expression.  Then she continued.  “His mother was human, and Stormygale bears her features.”  Athene was painfully aware that she was rattling on, but she really didn’t know where to begin, … what might be significant, where the problem truly had begun.<br>
<br>
“This year has been particularly hard.  Her mother died, and … a man … a man with whom she was very close passed from this world as well.  <br>
<br>
“Then a few months ago, her back was broken during a Claw attack on Xanamech Nexmirthafen in the Plane of Innovation.  … Usually, of course, such things heal immediately or over a short length of time, but not so this injury.  For whatever reason, rather than seek the attention of a competent cleric or shaman when the injury persisted, she sought the bottle … and solitude.”  Athene coughed and cleared her throat, not sure when Stormygale would break in to protest or to uncork another bottle in silent defiance.  So Athene quickly resumed her tale.  “In truth, both have served her well enough in the past.  Usually, … a few days or weeks away, and she returns renewed.  And her pain threshold is very high.  She has borne for months what can bring Saphron to her knees in one afternoon’s treatment.<br>
<br>
“It took us some time and some doing to get her here.  In the end, she came of her own accord.  But it has been some days now, and the pain has not fully abated.  Another shaman—one who helped us in the past—created a kind of poultice or treatment of some sort.  That worked well at first, but the pain persists.  We have not been able to locate him again—even to inquire as to what the remedy contained.<br>
<br>
“And now, … worse, I think, is this festering hatred that surrounds her.  She is consumed with rage, and …. I don’t know why.”  <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#212128><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub148.ezboard.com/bthewordsofnagafen.showUserPublicProfile?gid=stormygalewindrunner>Stormygale Windrunner</A>&nbsp; <IMG HEIGHT=10 WIDTH=10 SRC="http://www.cpmission.com/graphics/icons/icon45.gif" BORDER=0></span><br> <span class=usertitle>CoN Member</span><br>  Posts: 1024<br> <font color=#7A8798>(8/20/03 12:34 am)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub148.ezboard.com/fthewordsofnagafenmuirlansweeklypics.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=142.topic&index=107>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title>   Re: The Fraud</span><hr size=1> Stormygale watched and listened to Athene. Nervous Athene. Nervous Saphron. Nervous Kaly. Nervous Stormygale. Bewildered Kyusz. She chewed a fingernail as she listened, and watched the fire. <br>
<br>
She had come willingly, but now she didn't know why. There was no hope for her here.  Saphron could do nothing. The fact that her pain had forced that pompous little halfling unconscious made her giggle. <br>
<br>
The talking at the table came to an abrupt halt as they all turned to stare at her, with eyebrows raised, mouth open and alarmed looks all around. <br>
<br>
She knew they were all waiting for her next outburst. Well, it was their own fault. They brought her here promising hope, and everyday that hope slipped further and further away. She was beyond Saphron's scope. That was evident, but she'd known that already and such was the reason she'd tried so hard to avoid her. Why bother?<br>
<br>
And this Lizard, Kyusz. What was he supposed to do that Tondar couldn't? Tondar had been her friend for many a year and his medicine had helped for a bit, but it too had faded away like a wisp of wind. <br>
<br>
The only reason she hadn't left was for one, she was constantly watched now, and two, for some reason her mother's portrait seemed to speak to her. &quot;Stay...Have faith....Stay&quot;<br>
<br>
&quot;Where is my locket?&quot; she blurted, again stopping all conversation at the table. &quot; I must have my locket. My mother told me to wear it always and it's lost... lost.  Probably that sneak in Skyshrine. I want my locket!&quot;  She mumbled on about rogues and platinum pieces and then rose, ignoring everyone and the pain, as they watched in silence, and wandered off down the hall to get another bottle. Hell, she got three. Might as well since she was up. <br>
<br>
Walking back to her blankets by the fire, she sat on them while sucking on the first of the three bottles. After the second, her voce was slurring but she was still mumbling. <br>
<br>
Opening the third bottle so she could two fist them and not leave one behind, and because getting down and up weren't so easy, she rose and did a little triple step sideways, almost falling when her feet caught in the blanket. She disentangled herself with a vile oath, and then staggered and swayed over to the table where they all sat murmuring in a great grand conference. <br>
<br>
The great healers who couldn't heal. She thought that funny and laughed again. Laughed until the tears started to slide a snaky path down her cheeks, and started her hiccuping. <br>
<br>
She leaned over Athene and let her face get within inches. &quot;Where is my locket?!&quot; She bellowed. <br>
<br>
Athene pushed back from the table, or maybe the brandy breath, and gently said &quot; I don't know Stormy. Where did you lose it?&quot; <br>
<br>
&quot;Well if ah nu tha i'd kill tha bloody rogue wha stole it of me in Shy, in Sky *hic* in Shyskrine. Stole my money but din take it. What kinna rogue is tha? Left it onna *hic* onna *hic* floor for me ta fine when I woke up. But he took my locket. *hic* He gots it. I know he dose. Ma said onct. Ma said. *hic* She said never, ever,&quot; and here Stormygale punctuated her words with a pointed finger at Athene tipping the bottle in her hand and drippling brandy all over Athene's sleeve, &quot;ever take it off, see? Hey''ll get yu. *hic* The boogie man is gonna get me now.&quot; <br>
<br>
&quot;Who is the boogie man?&quot; Athene asked as she tried to wipe the brandy off her leather clad arm. <br>
<br>
&quot;Valath, Valtasi... *hic*... my father.&quot;<br>
<br>
With that stunning news Stormygale wove a meandering path back to her blankets and sat down to finish her brandy, her mother's portrait in her lap. <br>
