<br>
Within the great tree, in Abruzi’s old room, Stormygale was sleeping peacefully, at least for the moment.  It was almost as if she had shed some weighty burden in speaking of the locket and was able to breath easier--for now.  She had agreed to another treatment; and afterwards, had gone off to her mother’s room—sans alcohol—to sleep. <br>
<br>
Given some privacy and freedom to speak frankly, Athene continued. “She’s <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><em>always</em><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--> had Valt’s blood coursing through her veins, and she’s <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><em>often</em><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--> been more demon than fairy.”<br>
<br>
Saphron shook her head, unsure.  “I don’t know, Athene.  She spoke of some enchantment.  I remember when the portraits were commissioned.  Abruzi took the business quite seriously.  It would not surprise me that she would take such a step to protect her daughter.”<br>
<br>
Athene’s nodded.  “Aye, I remember that time also, but I don’t believe the enchantment was to protect Stormy from Valtathien.  You must recall too, before she left to open the tavern in Fironia Vie, Abruzi brought father and daughter together.  … And do you remember the miracle of Valt’s acceptance in Rivervale?  The day he walked into the vale, unchallenged by the guards?  I do not believe that Abruzi and Valtathien were at odds when she died nor in the years immediately preceding her death.  … However, I will find him and speak with him.”<br>
<br>
“Are you saying this is all in her head then?” asked Saphron, somewhat incredulous.  “Some kind of guilt over losing the locket?  No tug of war for her soul a going on?”<br>
<br>
Athene grimaced.  “No, Old Friend.  I didn’t say it was all in her head.  I said much, not all.  But, since you mentioned it, I do think guilt has a role in this too.  However, I fear worse, … much worse, than Valt and any influence he might have over her.”<br>
<br>
Saphron raised an eyebrow, clearly alarmed.  “Worse?  Speak on.  You’ve my attention.”<br>
<br>
The room had grown deathly quiet.  What more trouble could possibly lie around the bend?<br>
<br>
Athene spoke very slowly.  She had been puzzling it all out for some time.  “I do think the locket was enchanted, and I do think it connected mother and daughter.  I just wish Abruzi had thought it all out before she undertook such a measure.  Magic is so risky.  One can never see what its end result will be—how it will all play out.  <br>
<br>
“While Abruzi lived, the locket gave her a connection with her daughter beyond what was normal.  We shouldn’t forget that those lockets and the portraits were created when all those girls were in such endless trouble and were running off here and there, renegades for days on end.  Then, sometime later, the lockets were fashioned, and Abruzi told Stormygale to never take hers off.  … And apparently she didn’t.  But when Abruzi died, Stormygale felt the loss more keenly, I think, … than she might have.  Her mother’s presence in her life was made so viable, so very real, when Stormy possessed the locket and Abruzi was alive.  I don’t think Abruzi ever considered what it would be like for Stormygale when she died.”<br>
<br>
Saphron had taken a seat.  Now, she leaned forward, resting her elbows on the table before her, her chin in her hands.  She didn’t know where Athene was going with this theory, but some of what she said was true.  Abruzi had loved Stormygale beyond what was healthy, as many parents do.<br>
<br>
“Stormygale did not come to us, Saphron, until the locket was gone.  And I’m not certain now if she were coming to us, as much as she may have been coming to her mother.  She’s been clutching Abruzi’s portrait as though it were some sort of talisman.”<br>
<br>
“And what’s wrong with that, Athene?” Saphron countered.  “I mean, I know I chastised the girl, but she’s sick and she’s injured and she’s grieving.”<br>
<br>
“Aye, grieving, she is,” said Athene.  “For certain.  But who has the locket now?  And what was the exact enchantment placed upon it?  I suggest to you that the locket’s power is this: the bearer of the locket has some sway over the mind and the spirit of the ones whose portraits are within.  Abruzi is out of the world’s reach, but Stormygale is not.”  Athene sighed.  “Abruzi was a good mother, and she wanted to allow Stormygale to have free rein; but she wasn’t able to fully relinquish her hold.  She commissioned the portraits, and she had them imbued with magic—at great cost.  What will be the cost now?  Where is that locket?  … I think some evil may be pursuing her, but I don’t believe tis Valtathien.  In whose hand does that glittering piece now lie?” <p></p><i>Edited by: <A HREF=http://pub148.ezboard.com/bthewordsofnagafen.showUserPublicProfile?gid=athene>Athene</A>&nbsp; <IMG HEIGHT=10 WIDTH=10 SRC="http://home.mindspring.com/~abvogan/_uimages/ahstarsm.gif" BORDER=0> at: 8/21/03 6:19 am<br></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#212128><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub148.ezboard.com/bthewordsofnagafen.showUserPublicProfile?gid=kandiya>Kandiya</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Registered User</span><br>  Posts: 5<br> <font color=#7A8798>(8/21/03 8:59 am)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub148.ezboard.com/fthewordsofnagafenmuirlansweeklypics.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=142.topic&index=111>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title>   Re: The Fraud</span><hr size=1> Kandiya stirred from her blankets on the floor, looking around.<br>
&quot;How many days have passed?  How long have I been sleeping?  I must get to work immediately.&quot;  As she fumbled around the room trying to gather the few things she had brought with her, she started to recall the dreams.<br>
<br>
&quot;A female human, I remember her face well, she walked lost in my dreams.  And that dark shadow walked behind her as if stalking her.  There is so much to figure out, but yet I do not know where to begin.&quot;<br>
<br>
As Kandiya walked out of the tavern she lay a few hundred plat on the counter, &quot;This should be more than enough to cover the few days I have been here.&quot;  <br>
<br>
A chill passed through Thrugadin and Kandiya worked her way towards The Great Divide.  The cold chilled her already cold heart, and she dreaded the thought of spending any more time in this horrid place.<br>
<br>
Kandiya started asking everyone she could, describing the little halfing she saw, the human and all the other faces that she had recalled in her dream, but with no luck.  She had searched all over Vellious and sat on the beach near the otters.  She loved the music the otters played, it almost calmed her soul.  As she sat there with her head in her hands she glanced up to the tower where Skyshrine lay.  A familiar face was in the window looking down at her.<br>
<br>
&quot;Wait!  Wait!  I have been searching all over for you, please stay right there.&quot;  Digging a spirit of the wolf potion out of her bag she cast it upon herself to try and catch this person she saw.  Climbing to the top of the tower Kandiya realized there was no one there.  She sat down next to the wyverns.  &quot;What am I to do, this person is haunting me.  I swear I saw that human looking down at me from that window.&quot;  She wanted to cry.  Her head hurt as if someone had bonked her on the head with a huge hammer.  And she was so lost, but knew she had to find someone and tell them of this locket..........but who......where.....she put her head in her hands and tried to think. <p><!--EZCODE LINK START--><a href="http://www.magelo.com/eq_view_profile.html?num=457580"> Kandiya's things</a><!--EZCODE LINK END--><br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE IMAGE START--><img src="http://home.insightbb.com/~emetzler/angel_sig.gif"/><!--EZCODE IMAGE END--></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#141419><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub148.ezboard.com/bthewordsofnagafen.showUserPublicProfile?gid=saphronlafeete>Saphron LaFeete</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>CoN Member</span><br>  Posts: 88<br> <font color=#7A8798>(8/21/03 10:21 am)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub148.ezboard.com/fthewordsofnagafenmuirlansweeklypics.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=142.topic&index=112>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title>   Re: The Fraud</span><hr size=1> Saphron sat listening to Athene, slowly analyzing Athene's words. She was glad that she had began to sweeten Stormygale's teas with honey - and brandy. The druidess slept soundly now. <br>
<br>
&quot;Athene,&quot; Saphron began &quot;Your suspicions may be correct in some respects. Perhaps the connection between Abruzi and Stormygale was a bit extreme. However, they were bound to be close, considering Stormy's upbringing.<br>
<br>
&quot;But don't you remember the events just before Abruzi's passing? She visited a necromancer under the pretenses of healing. I think it was different. I think Abruzi knew she was beyond help, and that is why she visited the necromancer. Don't you see? Those lockets must be enchanted with essence emeralds. Part of Abruzi's very soul is within those lockets. And, who knows, perhaps part of Stormygale's as well.&quot;<br>
<br>
Athene stared at Saphron in disbelief.<br>
<br>
&quot;Athene, we have to get that locket back. Stormygale's immortal soul may depend on it. The absence of the locket may, indeed, be allowing Valtathien's influence to take hold. Or worse. And I think someone else knows it.&quot; <p><!--EZCODE LINK START--><a href="http://www.magelo.com/eq_view_profile.html?num=594544" target="top"><!--EZCODE FONT START--><span style="color:gold;font-family:Garamond;font-size:medium;">Saphron LaFeete</span><!--EZCODE FONT END--></a><!--EZCODE LINK END--> <!--EZCODE BR START--><br /><!--EZCODE BR END--> <!--EZCODE FONT START--><span style="color:purple;font-family:garamond;font-size:small;">High Priestess of Bristlebane </span><!--EZCODE FONT END--></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#212128><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title><A HREF="http://www.ezboard.com/promotions/csc.html" TARGET="_blank" ><IMG SRC="http://www.ezboard.com/image/cscicon3.gif" WIDTH="20" HEIGHT="20" BORDER="0" align="absmiddle"></A> <A HREF=http://pub148.ezboard.com/bthewordsofnagafen.showUserPublicProfile?gid=athene>Athene</A>&nbsp; <IMG HEIGHT=10 WIDTH=10 SRC="http://home.mindspring.com/~abvogan/_uimages/ahstarsm.gif" BORDER=0></span><br> <span class=usertitle>CoN Member</span><br>  Posts: 122<br> <font color=#7A8798>(8/21/03 6:32 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub148.ezboard.com/fthewordsofnagafenmuirlansweeklypics.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=142.topic&index=113>Reply</a>    <br>ezSupporter<br> </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title>   Re: The Fraud</span><hr size=1> <!--EZCODE IMAGE START--><img src="http://home.mindspring.com/~abvogan/sitebuildercontent/sitebuilderpictures/stormy.jpeg" style="border:0;"/><!--EZCODE IMAGE END--><!--EZCODE IMAGE START--><img src="http://home.mindspring.com/~abvogan/sitebuildercontent/sitebuilderpictures/locket.jpg" style="border:0;"/><!--EZCODE IMAGE END--><!--EZCODE IMAGE START--><img src="http://home.mindspring.com/~abvogan/sitebuildercontent/sitebuilderpictures/saffyre2.jpeg" style="border:0;"/><!--EZCODE IMAGE END--> <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#141419><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title><A HREF="http://www.ezboard.com/promotions/csc.html" TARGET="_blank" ><IMG SRC="http://www.ezboard.com/image/cscicon3.gif" WIDTH="20" HEIGHT="20" BORDER="0" align="absmiddle"></A> <A HREF=http://pub148.ezboard.com/bthewordsofnagafen.showUserPublicProfile?gid=athene>Athene</A>&nbsp; <IMG HEIGHT=10 WIDTH=10 SRC="http://home.mindspring.com/~abvogan/_uimages/ahstarsm.gif" BORDER=0></span><br> <span class=usertitle>CoN Member</span><br>  Posts: 123<br> <font color=#7A8798>(8/21/03 6:43 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub148.ezboard.com/fthewordsofnagafenmuirlansweeklypics.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=142.topic&index=114>Reply</a>    <br>ezSupporter<br> <BR><img src=http://home.mindspring.com/~abvogan/eye.JPG WIDTH=60 HEIGHT=60></td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title>   Re: The Fraud</span><hr size=1> Athene sat in the sunshine, her back against a strong oak on the edge of the glade.  Though she had always found the old guild tree warm and comfortable—cozy—she had begun to yearn for sunlight.  They had all been cooped up too long.    <br>
<br>
Stormygale was better, her back at least.  Saphron’s ministrations, with the help of the shaman, had begun to effect healing, but it was a slow process requiring Stormygale to be almost immobile much of the time.  Eventually, they had turned to an experimental treatment.  The intricacies of the procedure were lost on Athene, but in preparation for it, Stormygale had briefly recovered enough to spend some time among her guildmates in the Claw.  It was exhausting, however, and though the back was mending slowly, … Stormygale’s mental health was no better.<br>
<br>
The locket had not yet been found, and one could not determine what state of mind Stormygale might be in from one day to the next.  One moment she was raging and seemingly happy to be so—defiant, sharp tongued, and cruel.  Yet in another moment, she was childlike, fearful of what was happening to her, weak, but of sound mind.  They all tried to convince her that the mood swings were an unpleasant side effect of the herbs used in her treatment.  They spoke as little of the locket as they felt prudent, but assured her from time to time that they were searching for it diligently.  Actually, they were; this was not a ruse.  And Athene was looking for Valtathien.  <br>
<br>
Their paths had crossed once in the Plane of Tranquility, but they had barely had time to nod in each other’s direction before he left with a group of guildmates bound for Droga.  She had told him she needed to speak with him.  It was urgent, and it involved Stormygale.  He assured her she would hear from him, but then he was gone.  She could read nothing from his expression to indicate whether he knew anything about the current situation or not.  <br>
<br>
Saphron, Athene, Kalyndria, and a few others led a covert search for information.  They were wary of alerting too many to Stormygale’s unusual plight, even within the Claw, and so they spoke primarily to those they knew well.  The keeper of the locket might be within their very midst or maybe Valtathien <!--EZCODE UNDERLINE START--><span style="text-decoration:underline">did</span><!--EZCODE UNDERLINE END--> have it, though more and more, Athene felt it was someone they did not know.  <br>
<br>
The locket was valuable, even to one who was unaware of its powers.  <br>
<br>
Regularly, now, they wandered the Bazaar, hoping for the unlikely chance that the locket had been stolen and sold by the rogue of Skyshrine.  -–If there had even <!--EZCODE UNDERLINE START--><span style="text-decoration:underline">been</span><!--EZCODE UNDERLINE END--> a rogue.  Stormygale had awakened from a brandy-soaked dream to find it gone. She <!--EZCODE UNDERLINE START--><span style="text-decoration:underline">said</span><!--EZCODE UNDERLINE END--> a rogue had spied on her.  It was not unlikely.  If so, did the rogue follow her there expressly for the locket, or was it just a rogue’s luck that it found its way into his hand?<br>
<br>
While much of the guild focused on Stormygale’s recovery from her physical injury, a smaller faction now delved into matters of which they had little expertise.<br>
<br>
Saphron had reminded Athene of Abruzi and her necromancer “healer.”  Athene could not believe that she had forgotten it all.  It was in that time of so much turmoil that Athene had lost contact with Stormygale, but she had assumed Abruzi had made a full recovery and disassociated herself from her unusual choice of healer.  How had Salar put it when Athene had written him for advice at the time?  <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><em>“The arts taught in The Lodge of The Dead have little to do with healing.”</em><!--EZCODE ITALIC END-->   Now she wondered what had been the nature of that relationship and whether Saphron was right.  The locket had been imbued or enchanted with the emerald essence of Abruzi and maybe Stormygale, as well.<br>
<br>
If that were the case, did that lend the necromancer control over those souls if he again possessed the locket?  Could any of those trained within the lodge of the Dead exert such power?  What god had Abruzi’s necromancer followed?  Did it matter?  Was it all even related?<br>
<br>
Having no answer, Athene visited jewelry shop after jewelry shop in all the towns where she was welcome.  Maybe, maybe someone had seen that locket.  Maybe there <!--EZCODE UNDERLINE START--><span style="text-decoration:underline">was</span><!--EZCODE UNDERLINE END--> no evil one lurking--whispering urgently--in the shadows of Stormygale's dreams....<br>
 <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#212128><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub148.ezboard.com/bthewordsofnagafen.showUserPublicProfile?gid=kandiya>Kandiya</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Registered User</span><br>  Posts: 6<br> <font color=#7A8798>(8/27/03 11:10 am)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub148.ezboard.com/fthewordsofnagafenmuirlansweeklypics.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=142.topic&index=115>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title>   Re: The Fraud</span><hr size=1> Kandiya's heart sank and spirits dropped.  She was still unaware of whom she needed to seek out, where they could be hiding or even what their names were.<br>
<br>
After spending a few weeks wandering around velious she decided a break from this cold icey place was needed.  Meming gate she took herself back to the Plane of Knowledge.<br>
<br>
Mumbling to herself, &quot;I must find something to do to get my mind of this necklace, and all those faces I keep seeing.&quot;  Deciding a shopping trip was in order she made her way to the bazaar.  Haggling for good deals always made her feel better. <p><!--EZCODE LINK START--><a href="http://www.magelo.com/eq_view_profile.html?num=457580"> Kandiya's things</a><!--EZCODE LINK END--><br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE IMAGE START--><img src="http://home.insightbb.com/~emetzler/angel_sig.gif"/><!--EZCODE IMAGE END--></p><i>Edited by: <A HREF=http://pub148.ezboard.com/bthewordsofnagafen.showUserPublicProfile?gid=kandiya>Kandiya</A> at: 9/4/03 10:33 am<br></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#141419><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title><A HREF="http://www.ezboard.com/promotions/csc.html" TARGET="_blank" ><IMG SRC="http://www.ezboard.com/image/cscicon3.gif" WIDTH="20" HEIGHT="20" BORDER="0" align="absmiddle"></A> <A HREF=http://pub148.ezboard.com/bthewordsofnagafen.showUserPublicProfile?gid=athene>Athene</A>&nbsp; <IMG HEIGHT=10 WIDTH=10 SRC="http://home.mindspring.com/~abvogan/_uimages/ahstarsm.gif" BORDER=0></span><br> <span class=usertitle>CoN Member</span><br>  Posts: 127<br> <font color=#7A8798>(8/30/03 2:54 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub148.ezboard.com/fthewordsofnagafenmuirlansweeklypics.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=142.topic&index=116>Reply</a>    <br>ezSupporter<br> <BR><img src=http://home.mindspring.com/~abvogan/eye.JPG WIDTH=60 HEIGHT=60></td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title>   Re: The Fraud</span><hr size=1> Athene had finally been successful, at least in speaking with Stormygale's father for more than a few moments.  Their paths had crossed—again—in the Plane of Tranquility.  She was leaving the banking area.  Valtathien was just coming in the door.  She had looked up, surprised to see him. <br>
<br>
“I have time now if you do,” he said.<br>
<br>
In truth, she had only a few minutes. The last couple of weeks, she had spent in travel, to and from gift shops, jewelers, the Bazaar, and the old guild tree where Stormygale was often—still in recuperation.  Athene had spent very little time among her new guildmates in the Claw, and tonight she had planned to return to adventure among them.  “I can speak for a few moments,” she said, “and perhaps can meet soon?  The guild intends to raid the Keep of the Dain.” <br>
 <br>
“Bah, don’t tell me of those deeds,” said Valtathien, his face twisting into a grimace of disapproval.  The Dain and I have grown quite close.”<br>
<br>
“You have?   My, my.  How interesting. He enslaves his people, you know.  They are mindless, ... worse than gnomes!” she retorted, revealing an old prejudice and mistrust that had been with her since her youth and which she thought she had extinguished.<br>
<br>
Valtathien raised an eyebrow.  Here was the Athene of his youth, a bit brash, speaking her mind before thinking.  He chuckled.  “Yes, he’s quite an interesting fellow, and he only enslaves the ones that are a threat and have been allying themselves with the giants, who are the true evil. I’ve taken many a head from escaped slaves and traitors that have conspired with Tormaz.  The Dain even gave me a gift for my services, and he has a certain cleric assisting the general with safe travel to the gnomes of Iceclad very soon.” <br>
<br>
“Truly?  Arnellian?  That is news, indeed!”<br>
<br>
“Aye,” said Valtathien, motioning her away from the influx of people crowding the doorway of the bank. “Arnellian has become a priest of Brell, but he is misjudged by almost everyone still. He will always have that looming over him.”<br>
<br>
Together they walked toward the sandy beach shores.  Athene did not feel afraid.  Valtathien had been her enemy, true; but those days were long past.  They had been friends or wary allies for far longer.  She really did not believe he had anything to do with Stormygale’s trauma or the locket.  She studied his face—faint blue and handsome, but surely no longer cruel.  They stopped apart from any others and seated themselves on grass and rock. “You mean Arnellian is mistrusted because of his race?”   <br>
<br>
“Aye,” Valtathien nodded. “All anyone sees is a cleric of Innoruuk, but he left the temple long ago and pursued a new truth, and now he follows Brell.”<br>
<br>
“Brell?” said Athene, incredulous. Now, that was odd.  A former cleric of Innoruuk, now a follower of Brell?  <br>
<br>
“Aye, though he’s more of a lone cleric of Brell,” he conceded. “He gets no support at all from the Temple of Brell. In fact, they've try to kill him, but Brell knows the truth, and that’s all that matters to Arnellian.”<br>
<br>
Athene nodded. “True loyalty, which strangely leads me to ask you, Valt, …”<br>
<br>
“Yes?”<br>
<br>
“When Abruzi died, you were not enemies, were you?”<br>
<br>
“No, it’s hard to talk about that though.”<br>
<br>
“And you would wish no ill will upon Stormygale.  I am right in this, yes?”<br>
<br>
He eyes gleamed with fury. “Of course not, what kind of ridiculous question is that?” Athene watched his hands. Would he go for his sword?<br>
<br>
“I ask only because she believes you are pursuing her.” <br>
<br>
“She has said the same about you,” he said coldly.<br>
<br>
“At one point, yes, I was, but she came willingly in the end.  She was very sick. Her back has improved, but her state of mind is worse.”<br>
<br>
“Why does she say I pursue her?”<br>
<br>
“She believes that these dark thoughts she has ... are sent by you via a locket that she used to wear and lost. I do not, but I felt I had to see you and ask you directly. Someone <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><em>is</em><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--> after her, I believe.”<br>
<br>
“Well, take her to Arnellian then, and he can read her dreams and maybe find the source, but I assure you I’ll do everything I can to protect her from dangers that lurk.  … My past isn’t the cleanest, and I do have many enemies.”<br>
<br>
“Ah, .... it could be that there is some connection, but not in the matter than she thinks.  Perhaps someone uses her to get to you.” Athene stood. “I will seek out Arnellian.”<br>
<br>
“Good, then meet with me. Arnellian I’m sure will be around. He usually lurks around the Plane of Knowledge in the library. He studies much in his new faith though I honestly don’t know why he picked Brell. Why a silly cave dweller?”<br>
<br>
Athene smiled. “Heh, you have anticipated my next question.”<br>
<br>
“Ah, well. He’s been a good friend of mine through all these years and has been by my side. He helped when I worked for the Temple. He was there with me when I converted. He has always been somewhat of a learner, and I his teacher; and he has felt as I have for a long time about Innoruuk.”<br>
<br>
Athene had to go.  She could feel the urgency in the voices of the guild that wavered, back and forth, in her mind.  Still she stood, transfixed.  Valtathien was changed.  Surely, this was no act; and she regretted now that it was only this latest trouble concerning his daughter that had made her seek him out.  She watched him, and listened, almost hypnotized by his voice. <br>
<br>
“So when I started doing missions for the Dain, Arnellian started to get to know the people. He began making blankets for the poor and taking food to the elderly of Thurgadin. The Dain was so pleased by this, he ordered them to fashion together a new breastplate for him.”<br>
<br>
“He must have truly admired Arnellian's work.”<br>
<br>
“And so he was there for quite some time, and he eventually sat in a temple meeting and went to the front and prayed to Brell, and Brell answered and gave him a sacred etching. Thus, that is when he knew that he was accepted by Brell. He has tailored quite a nice prayer shawl, but he has this feeling that he will be given a great gift by Brell himself once he completes this mission for the Dain.”  Valtathien seemed to shake himself out of his reverie.  “Meet with me once you’ve met with Arnellian.  I shall await your visit.”<br>
<br>
Athene suppressed the urge to embrace Valtathien, to offer him some comfort.  She bowed and turned away.<br>
<br>
At the Plane of Knowledge portal, she was turned away.  None or very few were passing through.  Her own teleport spell cast her out into a dark night into nothingness.  Norrath was under some strange pervading spell.  Common travel was interrupted.  Many supposed some strange alignment of the stars had made it so. She turned away and made a camp on the beach. Tomorrow was another day, and perhaps it would dawn fair.<br>
