<br>
“How does a dark elf follow Brell?” questioned Saphron, clearly unconvinced of the news of Arnellian’s new allegiance.<br>
<br>
“He has apparently ingratiated himself with the Dain by perfomring good deeds and has gained his favor.  Sounds as if it were a genuine converstion, though the followers of Brell remain staunchly distrustful.”<br>
<br>
“Ah”<br>
<br>
“Valtathien denies having anything to do with Stormygale's mental torment and suggested we take her to Arnellian and have him seek to interpret her dreams.”<br>
<br>
“Bah!” snorted Saphron, incensed at such a suggestion. “What can an initiate cleric do that a real one cannot?!”<br>
<br>
“Now, now,” countered Athene. “I'm sure it was no attempt to discredit your own gifts.  I believe Valtathien meant merely that it might take one well used to the turnings of Innoruuk's mind to find one who follows him still.”<br>
<br>
Saphron stood simmering, indignant at the slight to her own healing arts, however unintentional.<br>
<br>
“Honestly, Saphron,” Athene continued, “he seemed to mean to only offer help.  Arnellian is somewhat of a channeler, I suppose.  He is gifted in reading dreams, or so Valtathien led me to believe. Of course, it could be a ruse if Valathien is truly behind Stormygale's mental torment, but I do not think that he is.”<br>
<br>
“I trust the followers of Innoruuk not,” said Saphron, her face glowering with displeasure.  <br>
<br>
Noting her friend's rage, Athene thought it best not to mention Saphron's steadfast allegiance to Salar, who was still a follower of Innoruuk as far as she knew.  On further consideration, she decided not to ask what deity Sinndee had grown up following either, though she suspected it was Innoruuk.  She opted instead for a weak, “Valathien no longer follows Innoruuk, or so he says.”<br>
<br>
“One is not so quickly changed,” countered Saphron.<br>
<br>
“But how long has it been truly since we were really in Valathien's company?  I have seen him only rarely for many seasons now,” said Athene. “Of course, you were guildmates with him recently.  I should not allow myself to forget that.”<br>
<br>
“Aye, that I was,” said Saphron evenly, “and I know him to be selfish and brooding.”<br>
<br>
Athene decided to leave it at that.  Even though she knew that Saphron had been deeply insulted by the suggestion that they take Stormygale to Arnellian, a junior cleric compared to herself, Athene still trusted her instincts.  She would be careful in her further dealings with Stormygale’s father.  It was important that she keep her wits about her.  The worst mistakes she had ever made in her life had come from decisions she had made based on emotion.  Human to the core, she was.<br>
